AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp;<span>“A pleasant site located between two small but prominent hills among which flows to the sea a very large river”. </span
<span> This is the first description of Nova Gallia, today's New York, edited by Giovanni Da Verrazzano, Florentine explorer at the service of the court of France >. &nbsp;It was him, in fact, on 17 April 1524 to sight, on board the Dauphine sailor, a deep and well protected cove, a natural port that stretched between lands covered with forests and lush plants. From Verrazzano was going up the Bay of New York > eighty years before London's Henry Hudson even though the story, for strange circumstances, attributed for centuries to the mission of the latter, on behalf of the Netherlands, this great discovery.</span>
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
At a distance of 500 years, however, the large screen will make a decisive contribution to bring back in the right perspective the extraordinary epoeia of which was protagonist 'Jean de Verrazane' (as he signed his missives from the New World to the French king). New York, on April 17, will celebrate the arrival of Dauphine between Staten Island and Brooklyn, &nbsp; with a new docufilm for the Rai and for American televisions - "Giovanni Da Verrazzano: From the Renaissance to New York City"> – which will premiere at the Paley Center of the Big Apple. An event in collaboration with the National Italian American Foundation (Niaf)> and the highest US and Italian institutions, in the presence of the city authorities and the director, Giuseppe Pedersoli.
&nbsp;
&nbsp; Produced by Beaver Lake Pictures in collaboration with Rai Documentari, with Alan Friedman as executive producer and producer Rai Gianluca Casagrande, the documentary – almost entirely filmed in Tuscany – sees Carlo Pedersoli> Jr. in the role of the Italian explorer and the actor Neri Marcoré > as a narrator. In the foreground the story of life and the journey of a character of strong human qualities that, thanks to the film, emerges in all its facets: fine observer and writer, skillful geographer and sailor because Giovanni Da Verrazzano was above all a Renaissance man.
&nbsp;
&nbsp; The film, preceded by a careful historical research, also gives a portrait of an explorer who “was in many ways more important than Christopher Columbus, because it was he who set foot in North America and map the entire eastern coast of the continent, from North Carolina to Newfoundland, while Colombo remained in the Caribbean”, highlights a note of ACSI (Amici della Cultura e della Storia Italiana) association that with the Tuscany Region, the Ministry of Culture
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Thanks to the work of the Florentine archivist Marco Calafati, they arrive - for the first time on film - the original documents on the loan granted in March 1523 by Banca Gondi, > found in the archives of the family. These are important pages that confirm the investment of 700 shields in the expedition of Da Verrazzano on the American eastern coasts (from North Carolina to Maine). An initial financing which, together with the intercessions of Antonio Gondi, proved decisive in obtaining the unforeseen approval of the journey by the King of France, Francis I.
&nbsp;
The anniversary celebrations will move on the other side of the Atlantic: in Florence>, the birthplace of the explorer, where the docufilm will be projected in national premiere, on 23 April, in the Salone dei 500 of Palazzo Vecchio> and will be inaugurated, on 24 April, an exhibition on the World Cartography from the '300 to the '500 realized with the support of the National Committee for the Anniversarys of the Presidency of the Council, the Tuscany Region, the Italian Military Geographical Institute and the CR Florence Foundation.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

