The Lebanese "Party of God" continued to scare Katiuscia rockets on the heights of the Golan until the early lights of dawn, when in Israel, at four in the morning, the invitation of the authorities to leave the shelters.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The President of the Council, Giorgia Meloni, chaired a meeting in videoconference of Heads of State and Government G7>. At the end of the discussion - we read in the final communiqué - the G7 leaders adopted a joint declaration that firmly condemns the launch of drones and missiles from Iran, reaffirming full support for the security of Israel. The G7 stressed the need to avoid further escalation, inviting the parties to refrain from actions aimed at sharpening tension in the region. To this end, the G7 appealed to end the crisis in Gaza through the cessation of hostilities and the release of the hostages by Hamas. Finally, they ensured the continuation of humanitarian aid to the Palestinian population.
&nbsp;
An army spokesman said at the press conference that Israel did not intend to hit Iran. "We are ready, we evaluate every scenario and at the moment we have no intention of extending our military operations," said Daniel Hagari, "we have endorsed both offensive and defensive plans."
&nbsp;
The Israeli prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, had ensured he was prepared to react and had a night telephone conversation with US President Joe Biden. Tel Aviv claims to have dropped 99% of drones and missiles, a success guaranteed by the support of U.S., Great Britain and Jordan.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
That 1% would have hit an air base in the Negev desert, causing infrastructure damage defined "very small" by Israel and "heavy" by Iran. A Bedouin girl would have been seriously injured by a splinter during the attack. All over the country, residents who resorted to medical care are about thirty, mostly contusi in fleeing to shelters.&nbsp;
Biden claimed to have contributed to neutralize "almost all" Iranian offensive means and will feel the allies of the G7, this year presided over by Italy, to agree a "unitarian diplomatic response" to the aggression of Tehran, > which was condemned by the western stationaries and the Secretary General of the UN, Antonio Guterres.

&nbsp;
At 22 Italians, at the request of Israel, the UN Security Council is convened. Russia, which had shown support to Iran after the attack on the consulate in Syria, was expressed only through its deputy representative at the Glass Palace, which paved a "new acute crisis".&nbsp; the United States does not want to attend an escalation> of the crisis in the Middle East, said the spokesman of the National Security Council of the White House, John Kirby. "We are not looking for a wider war with Iran," he added.
&nbsp;
China manifested "profound concern" and invited the parties to the "calm". Saudi Arabia and Egypt, which put its army in alert state, > asked the contenders for the "maximum moderation". The Israeli media have left Netanyahu's promise of a "meaning" or even "without precedent" reaction to the Iranian initiative. Washington immediately intervened to correct the shot.
According to the Israeli media, Biden, in his phone call with the Prime Minister of Tel Aviv, would have asked him not to react. The American warheads then give voice to high officials expressing concern for the "frenetic" military conduct of the ally and fear that Israel will respond franticly and disproportionately.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Something in the meantime moves and others well informed report shortly after the New York Times that Israel will coordinate its reaction with the allies.>&nbsp; The Iranian representation at the United Nations stated that it acted on the basis of the principle of self-defense > after what it considered an attack on its territory. And if Tehran hadn't responded to the blow of Damascus, internal pressure to the Islamic Republic would have gone up dangerously.
In the next few hours, the Israeli war cabinet will meet to assess the next steps. Biden, who in the official statements reiterated the support of "ferreo" to the defense of Israel, in private, according to the Nbc, would have been worried that Netanyahu is trying to drag the United States into a broader and deeper conflict.
&nbsp;
<h3> Iranian Parliament deputies celebrate the attack on Israel
<div </div
&nbsp;
The White House believes that the Israelis are not looking for a direct confrontation with Iran, in the light of the resources used in the war in Gaza, but it is not certain. Washington had considered the attack on the Iranian consulate too risky, judging it to be detrimental to the negotiations on the release of the prisoners of Hamas. "I don't think they had a strategy," he told the NBC a senior U.S. administration official, "the Israelis don't always make the best strategic decisions."
&nbsp;
_
<h3>Sunak: "Destructs from our Iranian drone planes"</h3>
The British Prime Minister, Rishi Sunak, confirmed that aircraft of the European Union's military air force were sent to the Middle East to demolish "an undetermined number of Iranian drones in response to the Tehran attack against Israel". In a statement to the BBC, the leader of the Conservatives said that "the international cooperation effort and the participation of the United Kingdom, should all missiles be intercepted, none in Israel, but also in neighbouring countries", such as Jordan.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h3> NATO condemns escalation and calls for moderation
NATO "condemns the escalation of Iran" and "invites moderation", so that "the conflict in the Middle East does not become uncontrollable". A spokesman for the Alliance said so. "We condemn escalation in Iran from day to day, we demand moderation and monitor developments closely. It is essential that conflict in the Middle East does not escape control," said Farah Dakhlallah
<h3> The US embassy in Israel: "Decrease threats, but caution"</h3>
The U.S. embassy in Jerusalem urged its compatriots to be cautious and asked all government employees and their relatives to limit their movements until further notice. "The threat of bombing of drones and/or missiles has decreased" reads in a note, and the indication of finding shelter "was revoked". "However - it adds - previous travel restrictions for U.S. government employees and their relatives remain in force. Personal travel is limited within and between Tel Aviv (including Herzliya, Netanya and Even Yehuda), Jerusalem and Be'er Sheva", we read in the statement. The embassy "will continue to monitor the security environment closely". The diplomatic headquarters let us know that "the schools in all Israel remain closed today. Many flights have been cancelled or delayed and travelers are encouraged to check with the airline the status of their flight. Land border crossings, including Allenby bridge crossing, are open." &nbsp;
<h3>Viminale, tomorrow the National Security Committee
The reflections on the security of the conflict in the Middle East will be at the heart of the National Committee for Public Order and Security, which will be chaired by the Interior Minister Matteo Piantedosi and will see the leadership of police forces and intelligence services. On the day of today the owner of the Viminale will be in telephone contact with the prefects of the major Italian cities, which in turn tomorrow could call Provincial Committees to make the point of the situation. Anti-terrorism vigilance is of course at the highest level on thousands of sensitive objectives, with particular attention to the approximately 250 targets considered at greater risk.&nbsp;
<h3>Tajani: "Tomorrow meeting of Arab ambassadors"</h3>
After the G7 video conference, in the morning there will be a meeting of Arab ambassadors: As Foreign Minister Antonio Tajani said, interviewed at RTL 102.5, "the goal of the Italian government, which also has the responsibility to lead the G7 is to take all the initiatives to avoid the worsening of the situation" after the Iranian attack of last night, "I stop remaining - he reiterated - that no one can think of erasing Israel from the map, as the extremists claim". Today, he recalled, the President of the Council will preside over the video conference of the leaders G7, in the morning there will be the meeting "of all ambassadors of the Arab countries; Tuesday I will meet the Canadian Foreign Minister and from Wednesday evening in Capri there will be the Foreign G7". On the agenda of all these next appointments, said the head of the Farnesina, there will be precisely the situation in the Middle East, "the reduction of tension and how to prevent the enlargement of the conflict. I hope that Israel adopts the rule of prudence and that there is no counterattack to the counterattack of Iran after the Israeli air force hit the consulate of Tehran in Syria while there was a meeting of the pasdarans with Hezbollah and Hamas".&nbsp;
<h3>Hamas: "The attack of Iran is a natural and deserved response"</h3>
"The military operation conducted by the Islamic Republic of Iran against Israel is a natural right and a well-deserved response to the crime of targeting the Iranian consulate in Damascus and the murder of several leaders of the revolutionary Guards." Hamas said so in a note.
<h3>Meloni condemns Iran's attacks
"The Italian government reiterates the condemnation of Iranian attacks against Israel. The Italian presidency of the G7 organized a conference for the first afternoon of today in connection with the leaders. We express a strong concern for further destabilization of the region and continue to work to avoid it." This is what the President of the Council Giorgia Meloni writes on social media.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h3> Israel raid in Northeast Lebanon
Israel would be hitting the Northeast of Lebanon with raids. Times of Israel cites the Lebanese media. The attack would target the city of Nabi Chit in the district of in Baalbek District, stronghold of Hezbollah, about 100 kilometers from the border. A source of the Islamist movement confirmed the raid.
<h3> Great Britain has made available the Typhoon of Raf</h3>
Britain has made available, in the joint defence operation from the Iranian attack on Israel, the Raf's Typhoon fighters. The Guardian reports it based on British defense sources. The operation of the United Kingdom was announced as an extension of long-standing Islamic State surveillance and bombing missions in Iraq and Syria, called Operation Shader.
<div </div
&nbsp;
During the night there was a wider appeal to stability by Prime Minister Rishi Sunak: "The United Kingdom will continue to defend the security of Israel and that of all our regional partners, including Jordan and Iraq. Together with our allies, we are working urgently to stabilize the situation and prevent further escalation. No one wants to see more bloodshed," said Premier.&nbsp;
<h3>Tajani: "It is a dangerous spiral, the G7 wants de-escalation"</h3>
"The Iranian retaliation of last night can start a dangerous spiral." The Foreign Minister Antonio Tajani said this by speaking to the Agorà broadcast on Rai3. No one, he said, must question the existence of the State of Israel. "We condemn the attack and consider it unacceptable to erase Israel from the map. We work to prevent an even stronger military crisis," he said. The G7 which will meet in video conferencing in the afternoon with the Italian presidency, added, aims at de-escalation. "The G7 will send messages to Israel, it is necessary to ensure that the situation is worse."
<h3>Herzog thanks the armed forces and allies
Israeli President Isaac Herzog thanked the Israeli army and allies after Iran launched about 300 drones and missiles attacking the country in an assault that was almost completely rejected. "Help you, dear soldiers and commanders of the IDF and the IAF. Bless the coalition of nations led by the United States and Potus," wrote Herzog on X.
&nbsp;
<div></div> "Bless my sisters and brothers, the people of Israel, for their exceptional demonstration of resilience. Together, the forces of good will overcome the forces of evil," the president wrote.
&nbsp;
<h3> Alarm sirens in Northern Israel bordering Lebanon
The sirens of the anti-racist alarms are resounding in northern Israel, near the border with Lebanon. Times of Israel.&nbsp;
<h3>Idf: "We acted closely with the US, Gb and France"</h3>
The Israeli army worked closely with the United States, the United Kingdom and France during the attack on Iran. Idf spokesman Daniel Hagari reported this, adding that the three countries "acted together" during Iranian attacks. "This partnership has always been close, but in the night it has manifested unusually," said Hagari.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h3> Jordan reopens airspace
Jordan reopened its airspace after closing it in the night, after Iran launched drones and missiles in an attack against Israel. The state TV reported it, citing the Jordanian aviation authorities, according to Times of Israel.
<h3>Austin and Blinken: "The aid to Israel is 'blind'"</h3>
The United States will not hesitate to protect its forces and support Israel. It is the line expressed in recent hours by the American Defence Minister, Lloyd Austin, and the Secretary of State Antony Blinken. Austin invited Iran to "immediately stop any further attack, even by its proxy forces." The United States, he added in a statement, does not "look for conflict" with Iran, but explained that "they will not hesitate to act to protect their forces and support the defense of Israel". "The US commitment to Israel's security is armored," Blinken said in a post on X, adding that "the US condemns Iran's attack on Israel".
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

